                            <comment id="17352" author="balex" created="Tue, 25 Apr 2006 13:37:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed in SVN.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17411" author="balex" created="Thu, 27 Apr 2006 10:23:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Luke requested a way of retrieving even expired sessions, for application administration features. A few alternatives were considered, including:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Renaming SessionRegistry.getAllSessions() to getUnexpiredSessions() and then also adding a getExpiredSessions() or getAllSessions().&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. Modifying the contract for SessionRegistry.getAllSessions() to return expired and non-expired sessions, performing expired session filtering inside calling code.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. Modifying SessionRegistry.getAllSessions() to accept an &quot;includeExpiredSessions&quot; argument and performing the filtering in the SessionRegistry implementation itself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Option three was selected, as it is the most performant and represents better encapsulation of session expiration detection behaviour. Implementations that do not provide access to expired sessions may have, for example, detected a true argument for &quot;includeExpiredSessions&quot; and thrown an UnsupportedOperationException. Option two would have required a separate iteration over the SessionRegistry-returned session information, which is an unnecessary cost when iteration is likely to already be occuring to build the return list inside the SessionRegistry implementation.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="125436" author="issuemaster" created="Sat, 6 Feb 2016 06:23:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/506&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/506&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
